That Calvus, whose exces- sive care in the stylistic polish of his speeches is well attested (cf. Cic. Brut. 82, 283 cited note c. 18 6), followed the same practice is intrinsically probable, although it is not elsewhere expressly so stated. In the rhetorical schools of the Empire, similar commentarii or ‘explicationes' (cf. Sen. Suas. II 10 clted c. 26 11) were drawn up for the purely pedagogio purpose of fur- nishing to pupils characteristic specimens of the proper treatment of oratorical themes. Aper means to say, therefore, that the still extant summaries of Calvus were highly esteemed at the expense of the excellent and far superior outlines prepared by modern rhetoii- cians which the blind admirers of the ancients disdainfully cast aside as worthless.
